    <p><strong>Centralizing Business at CES</strong><br> 
by Karen Chupka</p>
    <p>No sooner have we completed our audit of the 2009 International CES that we begin planning in earnest to make the 2010 International CES even better than the last show, which was billed as one of the best CES’ ever. In fact, in our 2009 post-show survey, 75 percent of CES attendees agreed that CES is the most important single event to attend for companies involved in the consumer electronics industry.<BR><BR>As you begin making your CES exhibit plans, we have news to share that can help increase the amount of business you do at the next CES.&nbsp; <BR><BR>At the end of this year’s show, we sought feedback from 2009 CES exhibitors and attendees about their strategies and priorities. CES exhibitors and attendees encouraged us to help them get business done by making it easier to have more meetings and visit more booths. This has become one of our key goals for the 2010 International CES, the world’s largest consumer technology tradeshow, and is one that we are actively working on for all CES exhibitors and attendees.<BR><BR>We are assisted in achieving this goal by the fact that we gained outdoor, lobby and meeting room space at the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC) because they have cancelled their construction plans.<BR><BR>I am pleased to announce that all of these developments are enabling us to centralize the 2010 CES show floor. The LVCC (North, Central and South Halls) and Hilton will now house a majority of our tradeshow floor exhibitors.&nbsp; <BR><BR>High-performance audio &amp; home theater exhibitors, otherwise known as HPA-HT, will remain in the Venetian suites and meeting rooms. The Venetian will continue to hold events like CES Unveiled and official press conferences.&nbsp; And we will continue to run the Venetian Express between the two venues, making it easy to get to and from these two exhibit areas.<BR><BR>This centralization strategy will enable smaller retailers, integrators and attendees who have business interest in multiple product categories at CES to more easily conduct business.&nbsp; <BR><BR>There are many other developments adding energy and excitement to the 2010 International CES. We welcome EHX@CES and many new installer, integrator and custom home electronics exhibitors to South Hall 2. <BR><BR>CES’ new iLounge Pavilion sold out in record time and quadrupled in size to accommodate exhibitor demand. This exhibit area, also in South Hall 2, will feature the largest display of iPod, iPhone and Mac technologies in CES show history.<BR><BR>We will have other exciting announcements like these throughout the coming months, all designed to ensure that CES continues to be the one “must attend” event of the year for the global CE industry.<BR><BR>I welcome the opportunity to hear from you about the LVCC centralization, new developments or anything related to the 2010 International CES. Please e-mail me or phone me should you want to discuss aspects of why the 2010 International CES is going to be one of our most successful shows to date. I can be reached at <A href="mailto:kchupka@CE.org">kchupka@CE.org</A>, phone: 703-907-7639.<BR><BR>Thank you for being part of the 2010 International CES. Together, we will achieve great things.
<P>Sincerely,</P>
<P><IMG src="/images/content/Karen-Chupka.jpg"></P></p>
